      "text": "**Adding Download Functionality**\n\nI'm now focused on incorporating a download button into the TriAttach app. My intention is to enable users to save the generated images directly after successful generation. The button should appear after the image is created, in both \"Generate Image\" and \"Image to Prompt\" modes. I'm exploring the best way to handle the file download process itself to ensure a smooth user experience.\n\n\n**Implementing Download Button**\n\nI've made progress on adding the download functionality. I'm focusing on incorporating a \"Download Image\" button directly after the generated image display in the output panel. This is specifically for the \"Generate Image\" mode. My goal is a visually consistent button that matches the existing styling, handled with Tailwind CSS. I'm now exploring how to trigger the download of the base64-encoded image data. I'm checking the logic in `App.tsx` and have a clean implementation in mind.\n\n\n**Adding Download Button in Logic**\n\nI'm now integrating the download button's logic within `App.tsx`. The button will appear conditionally: when an image (`generatedImage`) exists and the loading state (`isLoading`) is false, I'll add the button right after the `generatedImage` rendering. I intend to use a temporary anchor element to facilitate downloading the base64-encoded image data. This implementation looks clean. I'll test the logic.\n\n\n**Refining Download Button UI**\n\nI'm now refining the UI of the download button. My plan is to position it directly below the generated image. I've decided on a download icon and the Indonesian text \"Unduh Gambar\". It will mirror the style of the existing \"Salin Teks\" button for visual consistency. I'll place the button within the conditional rendering block to ensure it appears only when an image is available.\n\n```\n\n**Verifying API Integrations**\n\nI've confirmed `responseModalities` is already handled in `geminiService.ts`, so no changes there are needed. I'm proceeding to integrate the download button into `App.tsx`. My focus is a functional button below the generated image. Clicking it will download the base64-encoded image as a PNG. I will ensure the button's appearance matches the existing design, using a download icon and the Indonesian text \"Unduh Gambar\".\n\n\n**Integrating Download Logic**\n\nI'm now integrating the `handleDownload` function into `App.tsx`. I'll create a download button within the render function. This button will conditionally appear, right below the generated image, when an image is present. The `handleDownload` logic will use a temporary anchor element to trigger the download of the base64-encoded image as a PNG. I'll test that the file name is correctly set. I'll ensure the UI is consistent with existing buttons. I've double-checked the imports to confirm everything is in place, and the Gemini service seems fine as is.\n\n\n",
